<Layout title="Open Home Tips for Sellers: How to Prepare and What to Do on the Day | Daniel Gierach Property" description="A practical guide for Brisbane sellers on how to prepare for each open for inspection, what to do the day before, the morning of, and how to use buyer feedback to adjust your campaign." draft={draft}>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I be home during the open inspection?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. Buyers are uncomfortable commenting honestly on a property when the owner is present. It also puts your agent in a difficult position when managing price conversations. Leave the property before the open starts and let your agent do their job."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What should I do with my pets during an open home?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Remove pets entirely, take them to a friend's house, a groomer, or for a walk. Even buyers who love animals can be put off by pet odours, pet hair on furniture, or a dog that is stressed by strangers walking through the house. Pet removal is not optional if you want strong buyer engagement."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How many open homes should I hold each week?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "For most Brisbane inner east properties, one well-prepared open per week is more effective than multiple poorly prepared ones. If demand is strong, your agent may recommend a midweek session in addition to the Saturday open. More opens do not always equal more buyers, preparation quality matters more than frequency."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What feedback should I ask my agent for after each open?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Ask for: total attendee numbers, repeat visitors, any verbal offers or expressions of interest, and direct buyer feedback on presentation, price expectations, and what they liked or did not like. If attendance drops week-on-week without explanation, or price feedback is consistently lower than your guide, that is a signal to discuss strategy with your agent."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How long should an open home campaign run before reconsidering strategy?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "If a well-prepared property has run three to four opens with strong attendance but no offers, the issue is usually price. If attendance itself is low, the marketing or price guide may be misaligned with buyer expectations. Most inner east Brisbane campaigns that are correctly priced and prepared should generate offers within the first two to three weeks."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8">
